408–1453":"1408–1453","1335–1421":"1335–1421","1339–1421":"1339–1421","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1403":"1403","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1378":"1378","1421":"1421","1453":"1453","9 May 1421":"9. maj 1421","1430":"1430","1408":"1408","1339":"1339","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England":"Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England","Otteby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England"},"nl":{"1380–1430":"1380–1430","1371–1421":"1371–1421","1378–1433":"1378–1433","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1408–1453":"1408–1453","1335–1421":"1335–1421","1339–1421":"1339–1421","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1403":"1403","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1378":"1378","1421":"1421","1453":"1453","9 May 1421":"9 mei 1421","1430":"1430","1408":"1408","1339":"1339","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England":"Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England","Otteby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England"},"en":{"1380–1430":"1380–1430","1371–1421":"1371–1421","1378–1433":"1378–1433","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1408–1453":"1408–1453","1335–1421":"1335–1421","1339–1421":"1339–1421","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1403":"1403","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1378":"1378","1421":"1421","1453":"1453","9 May 1421":"9 May 1421","1430":"1430","1408":"1408","1339":"1339","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England":"Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England","Otteby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Smith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name denoting a worker in metal, especially iron, such as a blacksmith or farrier, from Middle English <i>smith</i> ‘smith’ (Old English <i>smith</i>, probably a derivative of <i>smītan</i> ‘to strike, hammer’). Early examples are also found in the Latin form   Faber  . Metal-working was one of the earliest occupations for which specialist skills were required, and its importance ensured that this term and its equivalents in other languages were the most widespread of all occupational surnames in Europe. Medieval smiths were important not only in making horseshoes, plowshares, and other domestic articles, but above all for their skill in forging swords, other weapons, and armor. This is also the most frequent of all surnames in the US. It is very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below). This surname (in any of the two possible English senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti. See also   Smither  .","English: from Middle English <i>smithe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smiththe</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, occupational, for someone who worked in one, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Smitha in King's Nympton (Devon). Compare   Smithey  .","Irish and Scottish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b>, Irish <b>Mac Gabhann</b> ‘son of the smith’. See   McGowan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Smithe","meanings":["(1997: 115;2007: 306; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smither","meanings":["English (Surrey): occupational name from Middle English <i>smith(i)ere</i>, <i>smeth(i)ere</i> ‘blacksmith’, a derivative of Middle English <i>smithen</i>, <i>smethen</i>, ‘to make (something) in metal, to forge’. Compare   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smithey","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): from Middle English <i>smithi</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old Norse <i>smithja</i>), used either as a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, or an occupational name for someone who worked in one. Compare   Smith   and   Smead  ."]},{"name":"Smyth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ronan, Aidan, Brigid, Conor, Eoin, Malachy, Paddy.","English: variant of   Smith  . This form of the surname is particularly common Ireland."]},{"name":"Smythe","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"McGowan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Siobhan, Cormac, Seamus, Aileen, Colm, Eithne, Kieran, Niall, Paddy.","Scottish and Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (a') Ghobhainn</b> or <b>Mac Gobhann</b> (Scottish) or <b>Mac (an) Ghabhann</b> (Irish), ‘son of (the) smith’. This name has also been Anglicized as   Smith   and   Smithson  ."]},{"name":"Smead","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>smeth(e)</i> ‘smith’, a phonetic variant of   Smith   1 that was widespread in medieval England, especially in south-eastern and south-western counties.","topographic, occupational, and habitational name from Middle English <i>smethe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smethe</i>), a side form of   Smith   2, for someone who lived and worked at a blacksmith's, or who lived in or came from a place so named, such as Smeeth (Kent) or Smeed Farm in Hastingleigh (Kent). Compare the synonymous   Smithey  ."]},{"name":"Faber","meanings":["German, Dutch, French (Alsace and Lorraine), and Danish; Slovak and Czech (mainly <b>Fáber</b>): occupational name from Latin <i>faber</i> ‘blacksmith’. At the time of the Reformation, it was much used as a humanistic name, a translation into Latin of vernacular surnames such as German   Schmidt   and Dutch   Smit  . Compare   Fabri   and   Fauber  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also part of a title. It was François Lefebvre, <i>sieur</i> Duplessis Faber from Paris, France, whose title <i>sieur Duplessis Faber</i> was shortened into the surname <i>Faber</i>. He married Marie-Madeleine Chorel in Champlain, QC, in 1689."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Smith was born in 1380, in Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England, her father, Robert de Willerby, was 45 and her mother, Isabella Otteby, was 41. She married Thomas Spencer in 1403. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1430, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1380–1430":"1380–1430","1371–1421":"1371–1421","1378–1433":"1378–1433","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1408–1453":"1408–1453","1335–1421":"1335–1421","1339–1421":"1339–1421","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1403":"1403","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1378":"1378","1421":"1421","1453":"1453","9 May 1421":"9. mai 1421","1430":"1430","1408":"1408","1339":"1339","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England":"Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England","Otteby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1380–1430":"1380–1430","1371–1421":"1371–1421","1378–1433":"1378–1433","1390–1477":"1390–1477","1408–1453":"1408–1453","1335–1421":"1335–1421","1339–1421":"1339–1421","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1403":"1403","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1378":"1378","1421":"1421","1453":"1453","9 May 1421":"9. toukokuuta 1421","1430":"1430","1408":"1408","1339":"1339","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England":"Tedburn St Mary, Devon, England","Otteby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England"},"fr":{"1380–1430":"1380–1430","1371–1421":"1371–1421","137